to the editor us courts become arbiters of global rights and wrongs front page june 21 rightly points out that in an increasingly globalized world domestic courts are beginning to extend their jurisdiction to embrace a more international approach toward human rights this is also exactly the direction in which the impending international criminal court will take the international cause of human rights and justice however fear of this new conception of international jurisdiction is also the principle on which the bush administration bases its opposition to the court the court will ensure that perpetrators of crimes against humanity genocide and war crimes will be brought to justice wherever they live and under internationally accepted definitions of crimes and judicial standards daniel skinner brooklyn june 21 2001 the writer is media director at the new york law and justice project

